    What does violet shampoo do to your hair?
    It features crushed violet pigments that neutralize style-ruining brassy and yellow tones. Hair stylists often tone bleached or blonde hair to neutralize brassy yellow and orange tones on bleached hair with a purple color. Purple shampoo is a great at-home solution for toning hair and preventing brassiness.

    How to use violet shampoo?
    An AI Overview is not available for this searchCan't generate an AI overview right now. Try again later.
    AI Overview
    To use purple shampoo, first wet and shampoo hair with a regular shampoo, then rinse. Apply purple shampoo to wet, damp hair, massage it through, and leave it on for the recommended time (often 2-5 minutes) before rinsing thoroughly. Follow with a conditioner to prevent dryness.
     
    Steps to Use Purple Shampoo
    1. 1. Wash and Rinse 
      • Start by washing your hair with your regular shampoo to remove dirt and product buildup. 
      • Rinse the regular shampoo out completely. 
    2. 2. Apply Purple Shampoo
      • Gently massage a generous amount of purple shampoo into your wet, damp hair. 
      • Distribute the product evenly, focusing on the brassy or yellow areas of your hair. 
      • The longer you leave it on, the more intense the toning will be. 
    3. 3. Rinse and Condition
      • Rinse your hair thoroughly to remove all the purple shampoo. 
      • Apply a conditioner, as purple shampoo can be drying. 
    Tips for Best Results
    • Frequency:
      Use purple shampoo every few washes instead of every time to avoid an overly toned or purple color. 
    • Conditioner is Key:
      Always follow up with a good conditioner or a hydrating treatment to keep hair moisturized. 
    • Don't Overdo It:
      Be cautious with the application time, especially with porous or lightened hair. 
    • Check the Bottle:
      Always refer to the specific instructions on your purple shampoo bottle, as recommended timings can vary.
